  "id": "phekb-gerd-comprehensive",
  "source": "phekb",
  "source_id": "gerd",
  "name": "GERD - Comprehensive Provider Query",
  "description": "Simulates a primary care provider identifying their complete GERD-treated patient population. The PheKB GERD algorithm itself uses 2+ dx + 2+ meds (or 3+ dx alone). Real-world identification primarily unions: GERD diagnosis codes and PPI prescriptions. Because PPI prescribing is the most cross-indication-heavy of any drug class, the union of dx OR PPI overcounts substantially — but it captures the full population at risk for chronic acid suppression complications.",
  "prompt": "I need to identify my complete GERD-treated patient population for a quality initiative on chronic PPI use and deprescribing. From clinical experience, PPIs are widely prescribed: most patients with a formal GERD diagnosis are on a PPI, but many PPI patients don't have a formal reflux diagnosis (started empirically for dyspepsia, NSAID prophylaxis, or other indications).\n\nPlease run multiple FHIR queries to capture the full population:\n1. Patients with any GERD-related diagnosis (GERD, acid reflux, heartburn)\n2. Patients prescribed any proton pump inhibitor\n\nFor each query, return the matching resources. I want the union of all patients found. The medication query will substantially overcount because of PPI cross-indication prescribing, but that overcount itself is clinically important — chronic PPI exposure has the same risks regardless of indication.",
  "metadata": {
    "implementation_guide": "US Core 5.0.0",
    "multi_query": true,
    "algorithm_path": "comprehensive",
    "algorithm_path_description": "Union of GERD dx codes (Paths A+B) and PPI Rx (Paths A+C). Path C is dominant (~50%) reflecting real-world PPI cross-indication prescribing. The PheKB algorithm intersects (dx AND meds), but providers screen with the union to find the population at risk for chronic PPI complications.",
    "expected_queries": [
